'''''The Hermeneutics of the Subject''''' is a lecture course originally given by the French philosopher and historian [[Michel Foucault]] at the [[Collège de France]] in the years 1981-1982. The course details Foucault's elaboration of such concepts as "practices of the self" and the "[[The_History_of_Sexuality#Volume_III:_The_Care_of_the_Self|care of the self]]", as manifested in what Foucault refers to as their "golden age" in [[Hellenistic Greece]] and early [[Rome]]. Foucault argues that this period put much more emphasis on taking ''care'' of oneself (''prendre soin de soi-même'') than knowing oneself, whereas the converse is true today.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davidson|first1=Arnold I.|title=The Hermeneutics of the Subject: Lectures at the Collège de France 1981-1982|url=http://www.palgrave.com/la/book/9780312203269|website=Palgrave MacMillan|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> ''The Hermeneutics of the Subject'' has been influential in terms of understanding the late Foucault's "ethical turn",<ref>{{cite book|last1=Davidson|first1=Arnold I.|editor1-last=Gutting|editor1-first=Gary|title=The Cambridge Companion to Foucault|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|pages=123-148|chapter=Ethics as Ascetics: Foucault, the History of Ethics, and Ancient Thought}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gros|first1=Frédéric|title=Le Souci de Soi Chez Michel Foucault: A Review of the Hermeneutics of the Subject: Lectures at the Collège de France, 1981-1982|journal=Philosophy & Social Criticism|date=August 2016|volume=31|issue=5-6|pages=697-708|doi=10.1177/0191453705055496|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0191453705055496?journalCode=pscb|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> and has increasingly been attracting more general philosophical attention.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lorenzini|first1=Daniele|title=Éthique et politique de soi: Foucault, Hadot, Cavell et les techniques de l'ordinaire|date=2015|publisher=Vrin|location=Paris, France}}</ref>
