[[File:SWAK.jpg|thumbnail|S.W.A.K. on the back of a letter c. 1942]]
'''World War II postal acronyms''' were first used to convey messages between servicemen and their sweethearts back home.  They were usually written on the back of the envelope.<ref>{{cite book|title=Portrait of a Decade: London Life 1945-1955|author=Douglas Sutherland|year=1988|isbn=0-245-54561-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SIiAAAAAIAAJ|page=25}}</ref>

The acronyms, possibly including some more recent additions, are:

* S.W.A.L.K. — Sealed With A Loving Kiss.  A variant is S.W.A.K. ("sealed with a kiss").<ref>{{cite book|last=Detzer|first=David|title=Thunder of the captains: the short summer in 1950|publisher=Crowell|year=1977|page=34|isbn=0-690-01202-0}}</ref> 
* V.E.N.I.C.E. — Very Excited Now I Caress Everywhere<ref>{{cite book|title=To the Letter|author=Simon Garfield|year=2013|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BJpvGUTkF6gC&printsec=frontcover&dq=to+the+letter&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7iyvVNGaAZLdoAThiILYCg&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=to%20the%20letter&f=false|page=400}}</ref>
* E.G.Y.P.T. — Eager to Grab/Eagerly Groping/Grasping Your Pretty Tits<ref name=bbtd/>
* B.U.R.M.A. — Be Undressed/Upstairs Ready My Angel<ref name=bbtd>{{cite book|title=The Big Book of Talking Dirty|author=Jonathon Green|year=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FcZfq9wdtKkC|isbn=0-304-36677-3|page=292}}</ref>
* R.A.D.I.O. Romance And Delight I Offer (often used with B.U.R.M.A.)
* H.O.L.L.A.N.D. — Hope Our Love Lives/Lasts And Never Dies
* I.T.A.L.Y. — I Trust And Love You or I'm Thinking About Loving You
* F.R.A.N.C.E. — Friendship Remains And Never Can End
* M.A.L.A.Y.A. — My Ardent Lips Await Your Arrival
* C.H.I.N.A. — Come Home I'm Naked Already{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
* C.H.I.P. — Come Home I'm Pregnant{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
* B.O.L.T.O.P. — Better On Lips Than On Paper{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
* N.O.R.W.I.C.H. — (k)Nickers Off Ready When I Come Home{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
* E.N.G.L.A.N.D. — Every Naked Girl Loves A Naked Dick{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
* C.A.P.S.T.A.N. — Can A Prick Stand Twice A Night{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
* L.O.W.E.S.T.O.F.T. — Legs Opened Wide Enter Slowly To Obtain Full Treatment{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
* E.D.I.N.B.U.R.G.H. — Erection Definitely Imminent Now Book Usual Room George Hotel{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}

[[Terry Pratchett]] parodied this briefly in his [[Discworld]] novel ''[[Going Postal]]''. His acronyms included L.A.N.C.R.E. and K.L.A.T.C.H. ([[Lancre]] and [[Klatch]] being two locations in the Discworld), although these were never officially expanded.

A [[Dirty Pretty Things (band)|Dirty Pretty Things]] song is named "B.U.R.M.A." after the postal acronym and contains the line 'Be Upstairs Ready My Angel'.

